**Write a C++ Function to Convert Markdown to HTML**

### Introduction

In this exercise, you will create a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown-formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML-formatted text.

### Requirements

- The function should accept a reference to a `std::string` as its input.
- The function should return a `std::string` containing the converted HTML text.
- The function should handle basic markdown syntax, including:
  - Headers
  - Bold and italic text
  - Unordered and ordered lists
  - Links
  - Images

### Implementation

#### Step 1: Define the Function Signature

First, define the function signature in the header file (`markdown_to_html.h`):
```cpp
std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown);
```

#### Step 2: Implement the Function

Next, implement the function in the source file (`markdown_to_html.cpp`):
```cpp
#include "markdown_to_html.h"

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Convert markdown to HTML
    std::string html = "";

    // TODO: Implement the markdown to HTML conversion logic

    return html;
}
```

#### Step 3: Add Markdown Conversion Logic

Now, add the markdown conversion logic to the function:
```cpp
#include "markdown_to_html.h"

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = "";

    // Convert headers
    if (markdown.find("#") != std::string::npos) {
        html += "<h" + std::to_string(markdown.find("#")) + ">";
        html += markdown.substr(markdown.find("#") + 1);
        html += "</h" + std::to_string(markdown.find("#")) + ">";
    }

    // Convert bold and italic text
    if (markdown.find("**") != std::string::npos) {
        html += "<b>";
        html += markdown.substr(markdown.find("**") + 2);
        html += "</b>";
    }
    if (markdown.find("__") != std::string::npos) {
        html += "<i>";
        html += markdown.substr(markdown.find("__") + 2);
        html += "</i>";
    }

    // Convert lists
    if (markdown.find("* ") != std::string::npos) {
        html += "<ul>";
        std::istringstream iss(markdown);
        std::string item;
        while (std::getline(iss, item, '\n')) {
            if (item.find("* ") != std::string::npos) {
                html += "<li>";
                html += item.substr(item.find("* ") + 2);
                html += "</li>";
            }
        }
        html += "</ul>";
    }
    if (markdown.find("1. ") != std::string::npos) {
        html += "<ol>";
        std::istringstream iss(markdown);
        std::string item;
        int counter = 1;
        while (std::getline(iss, item, '\n')) {
            if (item.find("1. ") != std::string::npos) {
                html += "<li>";
                html += std::to_string(counter) + ". ";
                html += item.substr(item.find("1. ") + 3);
                html += "</li>";
                counter++;
            }
        }
        html += "</ol>";
    }

    // Convert links
    if (markdown.find("[") != std::string::npos) {
        std::istringstream iss(markdown);
        std::string link;
        std::string label;
        while (std::getline(iss, link, '[')) {
            if (link.find("](") != std::string::npos) {
                label = link.substr(0, link.find("]"));
                link = link.substr(link.find("](") + 2);
                html += "<a href=\"" + link + "\">" + label + "</a>";
            }
        }
    }

    // Convert images
    if (markdown.find("![" != std::string::npos) {
        std::istringstream iss(markdown);
        std::string image;
        std::string alt;
        while (std::getline(iss, image, '![')) {
            if (image.find("]")) {
                alt = image.substr(0, image.find("]"));
                image = image.substr(image.find("](") + 2);
                html += "<img src=\"" + image + "\" alt=\"" + alt + "\" />";
            }
        }
    }

    return html;
}
```

#### Step 4: Test the Function

Finally, test the function to ensure it works correctly:
```cpp
#include "markdown_to_html.h"

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n\n**Bold** and __Italic__ text.\n\n- Item 1\n- Item 2\n\n1. Item 1\n2. Item 2\n\n[Link](https://example.com)\n\n![Image](https://example.com/image.png)";

    std::string html = markdown_to_html(markdown);

    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

### Conclusion

Congratulations! You have successfully created a C++ function that converts markdown to HTML. This function can be used to convert markdown-formatted text to HTML for display in a web browser or other application.

